{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608658/1957111601/0014.xml":{"full_text":"A-14\nTHE EVENING STAR. Washington, D. C.\nS.YICKDAY. NOVEMBER Ift. 1P67\na\u2014ay\u2022]\u2014f v ;l.>\u25a0\u2022>\u2014ffis'\u25a0l'MMWl\niWw JbF\n'\u2022^--J r JMKKBKr BBSs jmSSB?; J|HI s S^j\u00df\u00df\u00dfKgFjjStt\u00df\u00dfsf\u00dfslm\ny\u00bbH|\n*^j/ I H r i; k R\nHI 1 a L l dL d IHH\n1 fj v ill A w\na 1 l r B\nfllljrj! %s E A J^KV\n||g||g J|ME WK R A f|B .Wr*\" *','\u25a0\u2018>l^,*\nf y; K\u00bb4|f\nJV W-foy&m?\nSHOULD AULD ACQUAINTANCE BE FOR\nGOT\u2014Here are a dozen University of Virginia\nseniors who will play their final home game at\nCharlottesville today against the University of\nSouth Carolina. Left to right are Jlalph Knee-\nTerp Freshmen\nBeat Plebes on\nKick by Scott\nANNAPOLIS, Nov. 16 UP).\u2014\nMaryland\u2019s freshmen came up\nwith their \u201codd year\u201d victory\nover the Navy Plebes here yes\nterday, despite Halfback Joe\nBellino\u2019s spectacular 98-yard\ntouchdown dash for the Plebes\nIn the last four minutes of play.\nSince 1952 the squads have\nalternated victories. Navy win\nning on even years and the\n.young Terrapins on odd. Yes\nterday\u2019s game was played on\nmuddy Thompson Stadium\nfield.\nBellino's scoring romp came\nafter Maryland Tackle Irvin\nFaunce\u2019s punt rolled dead on\nthe Navy 1-foot line. After\none play, Bellino burst through\nright tackle and streaked 98\nyards down the sidelines with\na host of baby Terrapins chas\ning him.\nThe Winchester (Mass.) half\nback also figured in the missed\nconversion. Attempting to hold\nthe ball for the placement try,\nhe had to reach for a bad pass\nfrom center and the ball\nsquirted out of his hands.\nVincent Scott got Maryland\u2019s\ntouchdown on a 12-yard pass\nfrom Jim Head, and he also\nkicked the extra point that\neventually decided the issue.\nThat score came with one min\nute to go in the first quarter to\nclimax a drive of 71 yards.\nBefore that the Plebes had\ndriven from their own 15 to the\nMaryland 25, where in four\ncracks at the tough Maryland\nline they wound up with a\n4-yard loss.\nMaryland Frosh 7 0 0 o\u20147\nNavv Plebes 0 0 0 o\u20146 i\nScoring\u2014Maryland: Touchdown \u2014i\nScott (12. pass from Head Point\nafter touchdown\u2014Scott Navy; Touch\ndown\u2014Bellino <9B. run).\nFOOTBALL\nContinued From Page A-13\nsissippi-Tennessee game. The\nloser could meet Texas A&M\nhi the Cotton Bowl.\nVMI Out to Hold Lead\nVanderbilt tangles with\nFlorida, while Navy, which also\nis receptive to a bowl bid. plays\nGeorge Washington. VMI will\ntry to hold its Southern Con\nference lead against The Cita\ndel. Princeton and Yale renew\ntheir ancient Ivy League series.\nOther major games:\nEAST Cornell Dartmouth,\nPenn Columbia. Brown Har\nvard, Penn State-Holy Cross,\nColgate-Syracuse.\nSOUTH\u2014Georgia Tech-Ala\nbama. Mississippi State-LSU\n<n>, Florida State-Mississippi\nSouthern. North Carolina State-\nVirginia Tech. South Carolina-\nVirginia, West Virginia-Wake\nForest.\nMIDWEST lndiana-Mich\nigan. Kansas State-Mtssouri,\nColorado-Nebraska. Northwest\nern-Purdue, Oklahoma State-\nKansas. Cincinnati Tulsa,\nHouston-Wichita, Illinois-Wis\nconsin.\nSOUTHWEST Arkansas-\nSMU. TCU-TPxas, Hardin-Sim\nmons-Texas Tech. Texas West\nern-Arizona.\nFAR WEST Washinuton-\nCalifornia. Stanford Oregon\nState. Idaho-Washington State.\nUtah State-Dcnver, Air Force-\nUtah.\nYOU BE THE\nQUARTERBACK\nAnswer\n(Question on Page A-13)\nNo. 3is right. Temple's ball\non the Temple 21. NCAA rule\n6. sec. 3. art. 2 and 4 apply. A\nplayer blocked into a kick us\ndeemed not to have touched the\nkick unless his hand touched\nIt. Ball is dead when Gettys\nburg touches it.\n(Distributed by The Register and\nTribune Syndicate)\nhockbyscoreT\nFASTERN I t ACit'l\nCharlotte .Johnstown. 1\nPhiladelphia 1 Washington, 0.\nAMERICAN I E A till\nProvidence. 8 PuffaJo. m\nintrLnational i fton\nfort WaSe. ft. Toledo.\nrof, ft. Lcuiaville. 4 (overtime).\nRusevlyan Is Big Gun\nIn Terps' Upset Victory\nContinued From Face A-13,\nMiami\u2019s three-game winning\nstreak, and a four-game losing i\nstreak in this stadium by Mary- j\nland. The Terps had lost twice;\nto Miami and twice to Okla\nhoma here in four years.\nGunderman Gets Fumbles\nPerlo, in a crushing line\nbacking role, was*a standout\nalong with Rod Breedlove, who\nright now is the best guard in\nthe Atlantic Coast Conference:,\nTackle Kurt Schwarz and i\nstony-faced Wilbur Main, the\nNo. 2 center.\nTom Gunderman. the other\nstarting sophomore guard, three\ntimes pounced on fumbles. He|\nrecovered the fumbled opening\nkickoif on the Miami 27, re\ncovered a fumble by Curci the\nfirst time Miami had the ball,\nand in the third quarter when\nMiami was on the Terps\u2019 S.\nGunderman flopped on a\nfumble by Maury Guttman\nwhen Schwaz hit the No. 2\nMiami quarterback so hard the\nball squirted away.\nThe other fumble recovery\nwas by Ben Scotti, the fiery end\nwhose tremendous enthusiasm\nfor the game carried into the\ndressing room, where he led the\ncelebration. That gave Mary\nland nine fumble recoveries in\ntheir last two games against\nonly one loss. The loss was a\nharmless fumble by Perlo late\nin the game, when he was dead\ntired.\nDare had his best night since\nlosing the starting left half job.\n\u201cRabbit\u201d scooted 78 yards with j\nthe second half kickoff, and\nwould have gone 98 for a\ntouchdown had he not lost his\nstride in waiting for Main to\nget in position for a final block.\nSome Chanceu Missed\nBig Ed Cooke also had a big\nnight. He made a great grab\nof a Rusevlyan pass for 18\nyards and a first down to set\nup the second touchdown on\nthe Miami 6. And he made\nthe prettiest block of the night\nwhen he broke Dickie Lewis\nloose on a 31-yard sprint.\nThe Terps' three quarterbacks\nblended in nicely. Lewis was\nthe leading ball carrier with 51\nyards and he set up the field\ngoal by Fritsch, the No. 3 quar\nterback.\nFor a while it appeared\nMaryland was going to waste\nso many scoring opportunities\nthat it would give Miami heart\nfor a comeback. That was the:\ncase last week against Clem-|\nson. and two weeks in a row\nwould have been too for\nMont and everybody else.\nMaryland had first down on\nthe 4 after recovering the open\ning kickoff, but had to settle\nfor Fritsch\u2019s field goal. The 1\nTerps came back to score.\nRusevlyan's passes to Moose\nTurner. Cooke and Fred Hamil\nton covering first-down yard\nage and Perlo bulling over from\nthe 2 on fourth down for the:\ntouchdown.\nMiami trailed 10-0 for only\ntwo minutes. Curd\u2019s southpaw l\npasses and his deep pitchouts\nset up Varone's 7-yard touch\ni down pass. Ralph Hawkins,\noy prearranged plan with Main,\nstepped on Main's back and\nleaped to block Varone\u2019s try\nfor the extra point.\nThe Terps moved from their\n23 to the Miami 7. where\nit appeared a fourth down and\n7. Situation called for a\nfield goal try by Fritsch. That\nwould have been as good as a\ntouchdown, as it would have\nmeant a 13-6 lead.\nBut after calling Fritsch to\nl the side. Mont waved him back.'\nHe explained later he thought\nthe Terps had a pass play that\ni would work here. But Rusev\nlyan's throw was tipped by\nFIGHTS LAST NIGHT\nBv the Associated Ptmi\nNEW YORK.\u2014Q\u00abne rulimpr. lftp\u00bb*.\nWest Jordan, Utah, outpointed Neal\nRivers. Ift?. Las Vccas, Nat.. 10.\nMANILA Dommr Ursua. 114V 4\nManila, knocked out Johnny Jarratt.\n117% Australia. L\nMELBOURNE. Australia. 4 Charlia\nBrmth. 137% Melbourne. of\u2019point ad\nFranco Rostni. 137% Rome. jo.\nland, Jim Bakhtiar, an All-American fullback\ncandidate; Jim Keyser, Harold Outten, Scott\nTeunis, Fred Polzer, Pat Whitaker, Jim Chand\nler, Bob Williams, Henry Davenport, Joe White\nand Nelson Yarbrough.\u2014AP Wirephoto.\niVester Newcomb, Miami\u2019s fine\ncenter.\nMaryland came back to the\n9 from the Miami 44. but a\n1 15-yard holding penalty set\n'the mback. A 9-yard Rusev-i\nlyan-to-Turner pass moved\nclose enough for another field:\ngoal try by Fritsch, but John\nJust missed.\nThe final frustration fol\nlowed Dare\u2019s gallop with the\nsecond-half kickoff to the Hur\nricanes' 17. Maryland drew 35\nyards In penalties and finally\nhad to punt for the first time\nin the game.\nScotti Recovers Fumble\nScottl's fumble recovery gave\nthe ball right back to the Terps\nand they moved to score on\nDare's catch of a Rusevlyan\nflip from less than a yard out.\nThe Terps were In control\nafter this and primarily were\noccupied in holding onto the\nball, wasting time through the\nrest of the game and holding\nMiami out\u2019 of scoring territory.\nMont called for quiet In the\ndressing room while he made\nan announcement. But every\nbody knew what was coming\nand lt wasn\u2019t very quiet. He\ntold them they could soak up\nthis wonderful sunshine until\nSunday.\nMltml 0 o o\u2014 Si\nMirvUnd 10 O S O\u2014lB 1\nMiami icortnt: Touchdown\u2014Varonc\n(7, run>.\nMaryland acorlnc Touchdowna\u2014\nPerlo (3. fun): Dare m-vard past from\nRusevlyan!.\nConversions\u2014Rusevlyan.\nField Goal\u2014Fritsch (11 yards!.\nMIAMI\nLeft ende\u2014Hlldebrandt. Corey.\nLeft tacklee\u2014Kelly, Burdsall. Gard\nner.\nLeft tuarde\u2014Wallace. Crawford\nCentere\u2014Newcomh, otto. B. Stewart\nRlSht auards\u2014Hayes. Vaslloff.\nRltht tackles\u2014Greaves. Buonopane.\nNodollne.\nRight ends \u2014Oeati Poole. Mlrllovlch. I\nQuarterbacks Curd. Outtmhn,\nMitchell.\nLeft halfbacka\u2014Plevel. T. Stewart.\nRight halfbacke\u2014Blasko. Varone.\nRosbaugh\nPullbacks\u2014Sandte. Deideiich.\nMARYLAND\nLeft ende\u2014Cooke. Shifter\nLeft tackles\u2014Bchwara. Stefl, Car\nroll, Gardl.\nLett auarde\u2014Breedlove, Schwarts.\nTonettl.\nCenters\u2014Alderton. Main.\nRltht auards\u2014Ounderman. Decicco,\nKern.\nRltht tackles\u2014Healy. Plor. Brutly.\nRltht ande\u2014Scotti. Turner\nQuarterback!\u2014Lewis, Fritsch. Rusev\nlyaa\nLeft halfbacks\u2014Dore. Veradl. Kersh\nner.\nRight halfbackt\u2014Layman. Hamilton.\nHawkins\nPullbacks\u2014Perlo. Joyce.\n4 -v^mMPWr\nJJ I^^H^HP^SIPSr\nJ, if\nJr r yfl HL\nWWHIMW j|r >a\u00dfr jJ4\niyK Ai. -4 \u00ae^\u00bbv.\nHk jjJSMf J/m\n<VIH f*' yr- x\n-<m**jtUt M\nIw -M\n\u2022'&-!%\u00bb.A\n111 i |j\u00df\nTHIS ONE MISSED \u2014But the Terps got another chance anyway. Jim\nJoyce of Maryland was stopped on this attempted fourth-down 1-yard\nplunge for a touchdown in the third period of last night's game\nagainst Miami at Miami, but Miami was offside and the Terps made it\nthe next time fa a pass from Bob Rusevlyam to Howie Dare.\u2014AP Wire-*\nphoto. T\nBrown, Lions\nAgain to Open\nIvy League\nPRINCETON, N. J\u201e Nov. 16\n(Special).\u2014Brown and Colum\nbia again will play the first\ngame of the Ivy League foot\nball season, according to the\n1958 schedule announced today.\nThe Bruins and Lions played\neach other to open the sched\nule when the Ivy League first\nbecame official last year, and\nthey did the same this season.\nThe 28-game, round-robin\nschedule is:\nSeptember 27\u2014Brown it Columbia.\nOctober 4\u2014Columbia at Princeton;\nVale at Brown; Harvard at CorneU;\nPennsylvania at Dartmouth.\nOctober 11\u2014Dartmouth at Brown;\nYale at Columbia: Princeton at Penn\n.aylvania.\nOctober 18\u2014Brown at Pennsylvania;\nHarvard at Columbia: Cornell at Yale.\nOctober 26\u2014Princeton at CorneU:\nDartmouth at Harvard.\nNovember I\u2014Brown1 \u2014Brown at Princeton:\nCornell at Columbia: Dartmouth at\nYsle: Pennsylvania at Harvard.\nNovember B\u2014Cornel at Brown: Co\nlumbia at Dartmouth: Harvard at\nPrinceton: Pannsylania at Yale.\nNovember 15\u2014Brown at Harvard:\nColumbia at Pennsylvania. Dartmouth\nat Cornell; Princeton at Yalo.\nNovember 22 \u2014Dartmouth at Prince\nton: Yale at Harvard.\nNovember 27 \u2014Cornell at Pennayl\ntanla.\nSpartans and Irish\nWin Cross-Country\nCHICAGO, Nov. 16 UP).\u2014\nMichigan State captured its\nthird consecutive team crown,\nbut Minnesota's Len Edelen\n!won the individual champion\nship in the 43d annual Big Ten\ncross-country meet yesterday.\nIn the Central Collegiate\nConference meet which fol\nlowed Immediately at Wash\ni ington Park's 4-mile course,\nNotre Dame retained its team\nchampionship with John War\ndle of Western Michigan taking\nthe individual title.\nEdelen loosed a terrifies fin\nish kick to pass Michigan\nState\u2019s Crawford Kennedy in\nthe final 10 yards of the Big\nTen race. Edelen won by 3\nyards and was clocked in 21\nminutes 9.4 seconds on a soggy\nLakers' Surge\nTightens Race\nForWesfiead\nBy th* Associated Pr\u00abu\nSt. Louis, Detroit and Cincin\nnati today were virtually tied\nfor the Western Division lead\nIn the National Basketball\nAssociation with only 15 per\ncentage points separating\nthem. But warteh out for\nMinneapolis.\nThe Lakers, wno got off to\nthe wprse start possible\u2014seven\nlosses in seven games\u2014under\ntheir hew coach, George Mikan,\nwon their' second straight last\nnight to move into contention\nIn the West. They defeated\nDetroit, 112-104, and are only\ntwo games back.\nIn the other games last\nnight, Syracuse- downed St.\nLouis, 91-96, and Cincinnati\ndefeated New York 101-99.\nDick Schnittker scored 19\nof his 22 points in the second\nhalf as Minneapolis roared\nback from a 20-point deficit\nto pull it out. Bob Leonard\nand Vern Mikkelsen added to\nthe Laker total with 20 and 17\npoints, respectively. George\nYardley. of the Pistons had 31.\nThe Nats mated into third\nplace in the East as Dolph\nSchayes led the attack with\n24 points. Cliff Hagan was\nhigh scorer for the Hawks with\n22 points.\nClyde Lovellette paced the\nRoyals with 33 points as they\nbroke a four-game losing streak\nand handed the Knickerbockers\ntheir third straight loss. Dave\nPointek\u2019s two free throws with\n12 seconds left won it for Cin\ncinnati. Willie Naulls scored\n24 for New York.\nAfter much confusion George\nMikan remains pro basketball\u2019s\nall-time high scorer. Conflict\ning records were straightened\nout yesterday after it was first\nannounced Thursday night that\nSchayes had exceeded the for\nmer Laker great.\nThe records show Mikan with\n11,764 points in the old Na\ntional Basketball League and\nthe NBA. Ed Macauley has\nscored 10,272 points in NBA\nplay alone.\nSchayes is second to both\nwith 10,972 points in both\nleagues and 10.171 in the NBA.\nThe marks include regular sea\nson play only.\nT ulloch Wins\nIn Australia\nBRISBANE, Australia, Nov.\n16 UP). Australia\u2019s wonder\nhorse, Tulloch, made It nine\nwins In a row with an effortless\nvictory In the mile and one\nhalf Queensland Derby today.\nThe win also created an\nAustralian record of one horse\nwinning the coveted doubles In\nBrisbane, Sydney afid Mel-i\nbourne the Sires Produce!\nStakes for 2-year-olds and\nDerbies for 3-year-olds.\nThe 3-year-old Tulloch took\nthings quietly In the early\nstages of today\u2019s race when\nManinda led by 15 lengths.\nAfter a half mile Tulloch easily\noverhauled the leader, then!\npulled away to win by seven 1\nlengths in 2:32%.\nMon Frere finished second 1\nand Warblrl third as Maninda\nfaded to last in the 4-horse\nfield.\nMichaels' Four Goals\nBeat AU Soccermen\nWESTMINSTER, Md. n6v.\n16 (A>). \u2014With Gene Michaels\nmonopolizing the\nWestern Maryland defeated\nAmerican University. 4-3. yes\nterday in a Mason-Dixon Con\nference soccer contest.\nMichaels booted all four\nWestern Maryland goals, the\nlast with only two minutes re\nmaining to break a 3-3 tie. i\nRoger Williams, Jeff Bernard\nand Gerrich Radechevsky\n'scored for AU.\nFullmer Aiming at Title\nAfter Win Over Rivers\n\nNEW YORK. Nov. 16 UP).\u2014\n\u201cGive me a title fight any day.\nThis kind is do or die\u2014a real\nwar.\u201d\nBlood smeared Gene Full\nmer was talking to reporters 1\nin his dressing room last night\nafter winning a narrow de-\ncision over Neal Rivers. The i\n10-round Madison Square Gar-\nden bout was so close that one i\nofficial called it a draw. The i\nother two officials voted for i\nFullmer.\n\u201cThis was tougher than'\nfighting for the champion-\nship,\" Fullmer said. \"The pres-\nsure was just as great but not::\nthe reward. I bad everything i:\nto lose and he (Rivers) had 1\neverything to gain.\u201d\nMarv. Jenson, Fullmer\u2019s i\nmanager, will try to see to it\ntut the former middleweight I\nking, who held the title for i\nfour months earlier In the year; 1\ngoto another crack at the\ncrown.\nJenson handed out copies of i\na letter to him from Jim Nor- 1\nris, president of the Interna- 1\ntional Boxing Club. It was I\ndated April 23,1957, eight days l\nBi-County Title at Stake\nAs Blair and B-CC Clash\nMontgomery Blair's unbeaten\neleven and Bethesda Chevy\nChase, once beaten but still\npossessing a perfect record in\nleague play, battled for the\nMaryland Bi-County League\nchampionship today in their\nclash at 2 pm. at the Blair\nstadium.\nA homecoming crowd of 10.-\n000 fans was expected to the\nclimactical game of the season\nfor both teams. An automobile\ni parade highlighted pre-game\nfestivities and the contest it\nself was to be broadcast over\nWDON (1540 k.c.) starting at\n1:55.\nBlair, paced by Tommy\nParker-Gray\nGains Playoff\nCULPEPER, Va., Nov. 16\n(Special).\u2014Parker-Gray High\nSchool of Alexandria ran its\nwinning streak to nine straight\nwith a 19-0 victory over Carver\nHigh School here yesterday\nafternoon.\nThe Bulldogs, losers only to\nCardozo In their second game,\nfinished the season with a 10-1\nrecord and a berth in the Vir\nginia Interscholastic Associa\ntion playoff.\nParker-Gray took the open\ning kickoff and went 62 yards,\nin four plays for the touch\ndown. Quarterback Roland\nj Scott picked up 56 of the yards\nIncluding the last 15 for the\nscore.\nScott intercepted a pass in\nthe second period and then\nthrew a touchdown pass to\nLinwood Hyden from seven\nyards out for the Bulldogs\u2019 sec\nond score.\nCarver got off a bad punt\ndeep in its own territory in the\nfinal period. Parker-Gray took\nover on the 29. Four plays later, i\nLinwood Armstrong cracked\nthe middle of the line for the\ni score. Scott ran over the extra\npoint.\nU. S. Riders\nGain Honors\nTORONTO, Nov. 16 UP).\u2014\nCharles Dennehy of Lake For\nest. 111., rode Pillbox through\nthree faultless performances\nlast night to take first place in\nthe opening night individual\ni event of the International\njumping competitions at the\nRoyal Winter Fair.\nTed Williams of Britain was\nsecond on Pegasus with a clean\nfirst round and two clean jump\noffs. His time in the final\nround was 51.7 seconds, nearly\n10 seconds slower .than Denne\nhy\u2019s final round 41.9.\nThe United States also took\nthird place in the individual\nwith Hugh Wiley\u2019s rides on\nNautical. Wiley, from Towson.\nMd., rode Nautical hard and\nfast\u2014his time was 39.2 seconds\n\u2014but he knocked down the last\nJump of the 13-jump course\njfor four faults.\nFourth was Lt. W. A. Ring\nrose of Ireland on Ballynonty\nwith four faults in 40.7 seconds\nIn the final round.\nBryant Not Taking\nPost at Alabama\nHOUSTON. Tex.. Nov. 16 UP).\n\u2014Paul (Bear) Bryant. Texas\nA&M football coach, yesterday\ndenied reports ne would take\nthe head coaching job at the\n;University of Alabama.\nIn a terse statement, he said:.\n\u201cWe\u2019re fighting for our lives\nhere both tomorrow and on\nThanksgiving Day. I have rec-\nommended a coach for Ala\nbama. and it Isn't Paul Bryant.\u201d\nBryant, whose Aggies current\nly are rated the No. 1 college'\nfootball team in the Nation, has i\nseven years left on his contract'\nat A&M at $15,000 a year. He\nIs an Alabama graduate.\nNavy Booters Tied\nBy Swarthmore\nANNAPOLIS. Nov. 16 UP).\u2014\nNavy and Swarthmore soccer\nteams battled through two 10-\nminute overtime periods to a\nscoreless tie yesterday.\nI For the Tars it was their third\ntie of the season against four\nvictories and two defeats.\nSwarthmore had won six and\nlost one.\nIn the freshman match.\nSwarthmore scored In thd final\nperiod to shade tha Pltbek, 2-1.\nbefore Fullmer lost his title to\nSugar Ray Robinson cm a fifth\nround knockout.\nThe letter read in part:\n\u201cIn the event Robinson de\nfeats Fullmer, then the winner\nof the Robinson-Basilio contest\nwill meet Oene Fullmer in a\nmiddleweight title contest. We\nwill promote no middleweight\ntitle contest except one be\ntween Fullmer and the winner\nof the Robinson-Basilio con\ntest.\"\nCarmen Basilio, of course,\nwhipped Robinson, September\n23 They have an agreement\nifor a rematch but Robinson\ni still hasn\u2019t decided if he wants\nit.\nThere were reports yesterday\nthat Robinson finally had re\nceived $107,000 of his Septem\nber purse that had been held\nup by the Federal tax people.\nPerhaps he now will be more\nwilling to talk of the future.\nReferee Mark Conn ($-4)\nand Artie Aldala ($-3-1) scored\nlast night\u2019s televised bout for\nFullmer and Judge BUI Recht\nhad it even (4-4-2 in rounds\nand 6-6 In points).\nBrown and Charles (Red) Pryor,\nruled a slight favorite over\nB-CC, which nipped Blair last\nyear, 7-6, In the title game.\nBethesda was upset, 13-6, by\nWalter Johnson High School\nlast week, but its supporters\nblame that on the fact that the\nteam was looking ahead to to\nday\u2019s game.\nAt the same time Blair, also\nlooking ahead, was hard pressed\nto edge DeMatha, 7-6. It took\na 96-yard touchdown run with\na kickoff by Pryor, and his\nsuccessful try for extra point,\nto do It. Tfce victory was Blair\u2019s\neighth of the season and ele\nvated it to second place In area\nschoolboy rankings. B-CC ranks\nfourth.\nBethesda Is expected to rely\nchiefly on a single-wing forma\ntion, with an occasional T\nformation play thrown in for\nvariety. Ken Smith and Neal\nMcDuffie are tha B-CC backs\nBlair must stop.\nWoodward Aerials\nIn Final Quarter\nJolt Longfellow\nTailback Eddie Weber threw\ntwo touchdown passes In the\nlast four minutes of play to\ngive Woodward Prep a 19-13\nvictory over Longfellow School\nyesterday sfternoon at Long-:\nfellow.\ni Behind 13-7, Weber threw:\nscoring passes to End Don Jud\nson and Halfback Larry Jacobs\nfor the victory that gave Wood-\nI ward a 3-2 final season record,\ni Longfellow opened the scor\ning in the first period when\nHalfback Marty Felker cracked\nthe Woodward line for 4\nyards and a touchdown after\na 40-yard drive.\nWoodward tied the game in\nthe third period when Quarter\nback Lee Seracina went 1\nyard off tackle for a touch\ndown. Weber converted.\nFelker put Longfellow into\nthe lead in the final period\nwith a 10-yard touchdown run\naround left end.\nWeber then connected with\n;an 11-yard pass to Judson and\na 30-yard pass to Jacobs to\ngain the victory.\nOsbourn Rally\nOvercomes Lead\nHeld by Marshall\nMarshall High School scored\non the first play from scrim\nmage on a 52-yard pass play\nbut Osbourn High roared back\nfor three touchdowns In the\nfirst half and coasted to a 21-6\nvictory last night at Osbourn.\nQuarterback John Sisk\nthrew a 12-yard pass to his\nbrother John, who raced the\nrest of the way for the Mar\nshall touchdown.\nOsbourn drove 55 yards In\nthe first period for a touch\ndown with Quarterback Danny\nGarrett going over from the 3.\nNelson Elliott kicked the extra\npoint.\nAfter a blocked punt. Os\nbourn scored Its second touch\ndown in the second quarter as\nLeonard Harris slanted 37,\nyards off tackle. Elliott again\nconverted.\nElliott culminated a 38-yard\ndrive with a 3-yard plunge j\nfor a touchdown in the final!\nminutes of the second period.!\nA 30-yard pass from Garrett l\nto Tom Sanders set up the\nscore. Elliott added the extra\npoint.\nPaige-Jackson\n-Riddles Carver\nPaige-Jackson coasted to a\n127-0 victory over Carver of\nRockville yesterday afternoon\nat Rockville on the strength of\nthe passing of Quarterback\ni Bobby Branson, the running of\nHalfback Bobby Smith and the\ndefensive play of Joe Kemp.\nBranson capped a 55-yard\ndrive In the first-period with a\n2-yard plunge and then\nthrew a 20-yard touchdown\npass to Kirk Baylor.\nSmith set up the first score\nwith a 30-yard run and Kemp\nrecovered a fumble to pave the 1\nway for the second score.\nKemp Intercepted a pass on\nhis own 40 In the final period\nand returned it to midfield.\nBranson threw to Kemp for 25\nyards and Smith picked up 21\nto the Carver 4. Fullback Bill\nTaylor rammed over for the\ntouchdown.\nTackle Walter Brown got the\nfinal Paige-Jackson touchdown\nwhen he recovered a fumb* In\nthe Carver end zona.\nL. A. Petition\nLOS ANGELES, N\u00abr> 1$ UP).\n\u2014More than 11.000 signatures\nwere eliminated yesterday from\na petition which. If found to be\nsufficient, wffl put at least a\ntemporary straitjacket an the\nLos Angeles Dodgers plans for\na baseball stadium.\nThe first strike against the\npetition circulators PM called\nby City Clerk Walter ff. Peter\nson. Tha referendum petition\nwas filed Thursday with $2,180\nsignatures. The city clerk said\nhe eliminated 11,261 because\nin these cases the fftinfc pre\ncincts in which the dpnen live\nhad not been property identi\nfied.\nIt will take $1,757 valid sig\nnatures on the petition to force\na referendum election, 'jk\nMr. Peterson gaid the next\nstep will be to check the petition\nwith the remaining 70,919\nnames against the master list\nof registered voters. This will\nbegin Monday morning- By\nlaw Mr. Peterson has $0 days\nin which to check the petition.\nThe petition was filed by\ncritics of the city\u2019s real jestate\ndeal with the Dodgers for use\nof city-owned Chaves Ravine,\nnot far from City Ha\u00a3, for a\nstadium site. If the petition\nis found to have enough sig\nnatures of registered vsters the\ncity council will be required to\nset a date for an elettion, at\nwhich time voters can approve\nor disapprove of the'deal by\nwhich the Dodgers would ac\nquire the site.\nBelvoir Blanks\nNorfolk Navy\nForrest (Fob) James, former\nAuburn star, scored both touch\ndowns yesterday as Fort Bel\nvoir blanked Norfolk Navy, 14-0,\nin the final game of the season\nfor both teams.\nWith some 9,000 fans looking\non at Belvoir. James tool! a 24-\nyard pass from Quarterback\nSteve James, no relation, and\nran 52 yards for what proved to\nthe winning touchdown in\nthe second quarter.\nNorfolk\u2019s poor punting set up\nBelvoir\u2019s second touchdown, giv\ning the Engineers the ball on\nthe visitors\u2019 33-yard line In the\nlast period. James stored on\nthe sixth play with i 6-yard\nrun around right end. Ted\nWisniewski, formerly of the\nPittsburgh Steelers, added both\nextra points.\nNorfolk outplayed Belvoir in\ni the first period, but the En\ngineers\u2019 76-yard scoring pass\nevidently took all the wind otft\nof the Tars' sails.\nBelvoir finished with a 5-3-1\nrecord, while Norfdk won 6\nand lost 3.\nBelvoir 0 f 0 7\u201414\nNorfolk OOP 0\u2014 0\nSpecial Purse Race\nOn Final Card at\nMarlboro Raceway\nA seven event card, high\nlighted by the 25-lap feature\nand a race of champions for a\nspecial purse, winner-take-all.\nIs scheduled for i Marlboro\nMotor Raceway\u2019s final program\nof the season tomorrow, start\ning at 2 p.m.\nThe sportsman-stock car\nshow starts with three 10-lap\nheats, followed by a 10-lap con\nsolation race and three-lap\ntrophy dash. The 25-lap feature\nand special event come next.\nAmong the drivers expected\nto compete are Lionel Johnson,\nBill Gross, Mack Hanbury, Nace\nMattingly, Bill Morgan, Elmo\nLangley, Wally Gore and Clay\nEastridge.\nMeanwhile, the weekly drag\nracing will continue tomorrow\nat Old Dominion Speedway at\nManassas, Va.. with time trials\nfor Inexperienced drivers on\ntap at Aquasco. Md., Raceway.\nAction at both places begins at\n11 am.\nPIMLICO\nContinued From Page A-13\ncreated the 15-inch high bronze\nstatue, will be on hand.\nSuch other works by Mrs.\nDunwiddie as bronze statues of\nThird Brother, stakes-winnlng\nson of Prlncequlllo owned by\n|C. T. Chenery; Actios Harry, the\nchampion pacer, and Go Boy\nSerenade, champion Tennessee\nwalking horse, *no a figure of\na Jumping horse trill be put on\ndisplay for the remainder of the\nmonth.\nJewel\u2019s Reward, Maine\nChance Farms\u2019 hope In the rich\nPimlico Futurity next Satur\nday. arrived at Old Hilltop yes\nterday to be propped for the\nmile and -a sixteenth event\nwhich should decide the 2-year\nold championship for 1057.\nThe colt Is due to get two\nor three workouts before the\nrace. Trainer Ivan Parke felt\nthat his colt\u2019s disappointing\neffort in the recent Garden\nState Btakes could be partially\nattributed to his having only\none brief trial over the New\nJersey track before the race.\nJewel's Reward has won the\ni Tremont, Washington Park\nFuturity. Cowdln and Cham\npagne Stakes, and a victory\n.here might insure the title.\nSpring-like weather drew\n10.017 fans yesterday and bet\nting reached $821,338.\nSpeeding up of the races has\nmet with approval here. Yes\nterday the field went to the\npost at 4:07. Ordinarily post\ntime for the eighth race with a\n1 o'clock start would be 4:30\np.m. The management has In\ntroduced the plan In order to\nget the fans homeward boyftd\nbefors darkness.","height":"28312","width":"18043"}}
